came here...

1606
02:11:58,648 --> 02:12:01,276
there was nothing-
nothing.

1607
02:12:02,385 --> 02:12:05,081
The Vietnamese were nothing.

1608
02:12:06,823 --> 02:12:09,189
So we worked hard...

1609
02:12:09,292 --> 02:12:11,226
very hard, and brought...

1610
02:12:11,327 --> 02:12:14,922
the rubber from Brazil,
and then plant it here.

1611
02:12:16,099 --> 02:12:19,227
We took the Vietnamese,
work with them...

1612
02:12:20,136 --> 02:12:22,001
make something-

1613
02:12:22,105 --> 02:12:24,835
something out of nothing.

1614
02:12:24,941 --> 02:12:29,378
So when you ask me why
we want to stay here, Captain...

1615
02:12:30,980 --> 02:12:35,076
we want to stay here because
it's ours- it belongs to us.

1616
02:12:35,184 --> 02:12:37,084
It keeps our family together.

1617
02:12:38,988 --> 02:12:40,888
I mean, we fight for that.

1618
02:12:42,992 --> 02:12:47,326
While you Americans,
you are fighting for...

1619
02:12:47,430 --> 02:12:51,389
the biggest nothing in history.

1620
02:12:58,608 --> 02:13:03,477
I'm sorry, Captain. I will see
if your men need any help to...

1621
02:13:03,579 --> 02:13:05,672
repair your boat...

1622
02:13:05,782 --> 02:13:08,808
so that you can go on
with your war.

1623
02:13:44,487 --> 02:13:47,388
I apologize
for my family, Captain.

1624
02:13:48,958 --> 02:13:51,256
We have all lost much here.

1625
02:13:52,495 --> 02:13:55,293
Hubert- his wife
and two sons.

1626
02:14:00,169 --> 02:14:02,399
And I have lost a husband.

1627
02:14:08,244 --> 02:14:10,007
I understand.

1628
02:14:10,113 --> 02:14:12,638
You are tired of the war.

1629
02:14:14,317 --> 02:14:16,877
I can see it in your face.

1630
02:14:18,888 --> 02:14:22,949
'Twas the same in the eyes
of the soldiers of our war.

1631
02:14:24,427 --> 02:14:28,124
<i>We called them
"Les Soldats Perdus-"</i>

1632
02:14:28,231 --> 02:14:30,461
The Lost Soldiers.

1633
02:14:35,171 --> 02:14:37,696
If you like,
we can have some cognac.

1634
02:14:44,881 --> 02:14:47,975
I have to-
to see about my men and-

1635
02:14:55,224 --> 02:14:58,125
The war will be
still here tomorrow.

1636
02:15:08,371 --> 02:15:10,601
Yeah, I guess you're right.

1637
02:15:18,648 --> 02:15:21,378
I noticed you had
no wine at dinner.

1638
02:15:22,485 --> 02:15:25,579
No, I don't drink wine.

1639
02:15:28,624 --> 02:15:32,720
I do like cognac, but I don't want
any now. Thank you.

1640
02:15:34,030 --> 02:15:36,464
Well...

1641
02:15:36,566 --> 02:15:39,626
then I-
I must drink alone.

1642
02:15:49,879 --> 02:15:53,076
Will you go back
after the war to America?

1643
02:15:58,754 --> 02:16:02,212
Then you're like us-
your home is here.

1644
02:16:19,642 --> 02:16:23,544
Do you know why you can never step
into the same river twice?

1645
02:16:25,781 --> 02:16:29,342
Yeah. 'Cause it's always moving.

1646
02:16:30,486 --> 02:16:34,354
I used to prepare
a pipe for my husband.

1647
02:16:40,763 --> 02:16:45,063
'Twas the morphine he took for
the wounds he suffered in his heart.

1648
02:16:48,404 --> 02:16:52,568
He would rage and he would cry,
my lost soldier.

1649
02:16:56,212 --> 02:17:00,171
And I said to him,
"There are two of you.

1650
02:17:00,283 --> 02:17:02,911
Don't you see?

1651
02:17:03,019 --> 02:17:06,921
One that kills
and one that loves."

1652
02:17:08,858 --> 02:17:11,053
And he said to me...

1653
02:17:11,160 --> 02:17:15,893
"I don't know whether
I'm an animal or a god."

1654
02:17:18,401 --> 02:17:20,301
But you are both.

1655
02:18:02,278 --> 02:18:04,178
You want more?

1656
02:18:09,585 --> 02:18:13,316
All that matters
is that you're alive.

1657
02:18:15,024 --> 02:18:17,788
You are alive, Captain.

1658
02:18:21,364 --> 02:18:23,594
That's the truth.

1659
02:19:36,705 --> 02:19:39,538
There are two of you,
don't you see?

1660
02:19:41,577 --> 02:19:44,068
One that kills...

1661
02:19:44,180 --> 02:19:46,546
and one that loves.

1662
02:20:15,077 --> 02:20:17,978
Can't see nothing.
We stoppin'.

1663
02:20:18,080 --> 02:20:20,640
You're not authorized
to stop this boat, Chief.

1664
02:20:20,749 --> 02:20:24,241
I said I can't see a thing, Captain.
I'm stopping this boat.

1665
02:20:24,353 --> 02:20:26,253
I ain't riskin'
no more lives.

1666
02:20:26,355 --> 02:20:29,085
I'm in command here, goddamn it.
You'll do what I say.

1667
02:20:30,860 --> 02:20:32,760
You see anything, Chef?

1668
02:20:35,131 --> 02:20:37,861
Why don't they
fucking attack, man?

1669
02:20:56,385 --> 02:20:58,512
Watch it over here, Chief.

1670
02:20:59,488 --> 02:21:01,456
Got a stump.

1671
02:21:04,326 --> 02:21:06,021
On the fifties.

1672
02:21:06,128 --> 02:21:08,528
<i>He was close.</i>

1673
02:21:09,965 --> 02:21:12,126
<i>He was real close.</i>

1674
02:21:13,235 --> 02:21:16,693
<i>I couldn't see him yet,
but I could feel him...</i>

1675
02:21:16,805 --> 02:21:18,773
<i>as if the boat were being
sucked upriver...</i>

1676
02:21:18,874 --> 02:21:21,707
<i>and the water was
flowing back into the jungle.</i>

1677
02:21:24,246 --> 02:21:26,146
<i>Whatever was going to happen...</i>

1678
02:21:26,248 --> 02:21:30,150
<i>it wasn't going to be the way
they called it back in Nha Trang.</i>

1679
02:21:35,257 --> 02:21:37,623
- Arrows!
- Fire!

1680
02:21:39,962 --> 02:21:42,829
Chef, open up! Fire!

1681
02:21:46,001 --> 02:21:48,299
Lance, fire!

1682
02:21:56,045 --> 02:22:00,004
Chef! Chef, it's okay.
Quit firing.

1683
02:22:00,115 --> 02:22:03,778
- They're just little toy arrows.
- Cut it out! Quiet!

1684
02:22:03,886 --> 02:22:06,855
Chief, tell them
to hold their fire!

1685
02:22:06,956 --> 02:22:09,516
They're just little sticks.
They're just trying to scare us.

1686
02:22:09,625 --> 02:22:11,616
Quiet!

1687
02:22:11,727 --> 02:22:14,628
You got us into this mess,
and now you can't get us out...

1688
02:22:14,730 --> 02:22:17,198
because you don't know where
the hell you're going, do ya?

1689
02:22:17,299 --> 02:22:19,426
Do ya?

1690
02:22:19,535 --> 02:22:22,698
You son of a bitch!
You bastard!

1691
02:22:24,240 --> 02:22:26,504
Lance, get the wheel!

1692
02:22:26,609 --> 02:22:30,841
You savages! Come and get it!
You son of a bitches!

1693
02:22:51,133 --> 02:22:52,691
A spear?

1694
02:24:12,247 --> 02:24:15,410
My mission is to make it
up into Cambodia.

1695
02:24:15,517 --> 02:24:18,452
There's a Green Beret colonel
up there who's gone insane...

1696
02:24:18,554 --> 02:24:19,953
and I'm supposed to kill him.

1697
02:24:21,423 --> 02:24:24,358
That's fucking typical!
Shit!

1698
02:24:24,460 --> 02:24:26,724
Fuckin' Vietnam mission!

1699
02:24:26,829 --> 02:24:30,526
I'm short and we gotta go up there
so you can kill one of our own guys?

1700
02:24:30,632 --> 02:24:34,329
That's fucking great!
That's just fucking great, man.

1701
02:24:34,436 --> 02:24:38,600
Shit!
That's fuckin' crazy.

1702
02:24:38,707 --> 02:24:41,676
I mean, I thought you were
going in to blow up a bridge...

1703
02:24:41,777 --> 02:24:45,076
or some fuckin'
railroad tracks or somethin'.

1704
02:24:45,180 --> 02:24:47,648
- That's all right.
- No. No, wait. Wait.

1705
02:24:47,750 --> 02:24:51,117
We'll go together, on the boat.
We'll go with you.

1706
02:24:51,220 --> 02:24:55,623
We'll go up there,
but on the boat. Okay?

1707
02:26:01,690 --> 02:26:04,181
<i>Part of me was afraid
of what I would find...</i>

1708
02:26:04,293 --> 02:26:06,693
<i>and what I would do
when I got there.</i>

1709
02:26:08,664 --> 02:26:11,497
<i>I knew the risks...</i>

1710
02:26:11,600 --> 02:26:13,898
<i>or imagined I knew.</i>

1711
02:26:15,838 --> 02:26:18,398
<i>But the thing
I felt the most...</i>

1712
02:26:18,507 --> 02:26:21,601
<i>much stronger than fear...</i>

1713
02:26:21,710 --> 02:26:24,440
<i>was the desire to confront him.</i>

1714
02:27:36,251 --> 02:27:38,310
Just keep movin'.

1715
02:27:38,420 --> 02:27:42,550
Lance, keep your hands
away from the guns.

1716
02:29:09,344 --> 02:29:11,938
It's all right! It's all right!
It's all been approved!

1717
02:29:13,315 --> 02:29:16,341
I ain't comin' in there!
Them bastards attacked us!

1718
02:29:16,451 --> 02:29:20,945
Hey, zap 'em with your siren, man.
Zap 'em with your siren.

1719
02:29:31,166 --> 02:29:33,430
There's mines over there
and mines over there too.

1720
02:29:33,535 --> 02:29:36,732
And watch out. Those goddamn
monkeys will bite you, I'll tell you.

1721
02:29:36,838 --> 02:29:40,035
Ah, that's a pretty one.
Move it right in towards me.

1722
02:29:40,142 --> 02:29:41,905
I'm an American.

1723
02:29:42,010 --> 02:29:44,808
Yeah. An American civilian.
Hi, Yanks.

1724
02:29:44,913 --> 02:29:47,404
Hi. American.

1725
02:29:47,516 --> 02:29:49,609
American civilian.
It's all right.

1726
02:29:49,718 --> 02:29:53,586
And you got the cigarettes. And that's
what I've been dreaming about.

1727
02:29:55,590 --> 02:29:58,354
- Who are you?
- Who are you?

1728
02:30:02,397 --> 02:30:04,024
I'm a photojournalist.

1729
02:30:04,132 --> 02:30:06,828
I've covered the war
since '64.

1730
02:30:06,935 --> 02:30:09,495
I've been in Laos,
Cambodia and 'Nam.

1731
02:30:12,841 --> 02:30:16,971
Hoo-wee, baby. I'll tell you one thing.
This boat is a mess, man.

1732
02:30:17,079 --> 02:30:19,343
Who are all these people?

1733
02:30:19,448 --> 02:30:23,248
Yeah, well, they think
you've come to-

1734
02:30:23,351 --> 02:30:24,682
to take him away.

1735
02:30:24,786 --> 02:30:27,949
- And I hope that isn't true.
- Take who away?

1736
02:30:30,125 --> 02:30:33,424
Him! Col. Kurtz.

1737
02:30:33,528 --> 02:30:37,294
These are all his children,
man, as far as you can see.

1738
02:30:37,399 --> 02:30:41,096
Hell, man, out here
we're all his children.

1739
02:30:41,203 --> 02:30:44,866
Could we talk to Col. Kurtz?

1740
02:30:44,973 --> 02:30:49,205
Hey, mac.
You don't talk to the colonel.

1741
02:30:49,311 --> 02:30:51,211
Well, you listen to him.

1742
02:30:51,313 --> 02:30:54,578
The man's enlarged my mind.

1743
02:30:54,683 --> 02:30:58,380
He's a poet warrior
in the classic sense.

1744
02:30:58,487 --> 02:31:00,387
I mean, sometimes he'll-

1745
02:31:00,489 --> 02:31:02,081
Well, you say hello to him,
right?

1746
02:31:02,190 --> 02:31:04,590
He'll just walk by you
and he won't even notice you.

1747
02:31:04,693 --> 02:31:08,322
Then suddenly he'll grab you and he'll
throw you in a corner and he'll say...

1748
02:31:08,430 --> 02:31:10,421
"Do you know that 'if'
is the middle word in 'life'?

1749
02:31:10,532 --> 02:31:13,433
If you can keep your head when all about
you are losing theirs and blaming you.

1750
02:31:13,535 --> 02:31:15,867
If you can trust yourself
when all men doubt you."

1751
02:31:15,971 --> 02:31:19,065
I'm a little man. I'm a little man.
He's a great man.

1752
02:31:19,174 --> 02:31:22,302
"I should have been
a pair of ragged claws...

1753
02:31:22,410 --> 02:31:25,277
scuttling across floors
of silent seas."

1754
02:31:25,380 --> 02:31:27,610
- I mean-
- Stay with the boat.

1755
02:31:27,716 --> 02:31:32,153
Don't go any- Don't go without me,
okay? I wanna get a picture.

1756
02:31:33,922 --> 02:31:37,289
He can be terrible
and he can be mean...

1757
02:31:37,392 --> 02:31:39,292
and he can be right.

1758
02:31:39,394 --> 02:31:42,420
He's fighting the war.
He's a great man.

1759
02:31:45,834 --> 02:31:47,734
I mean-

1760
02:31:50,272 --> 02:31:53,799
I wish I had words, you know.
I wish I had words.

1761
02:31:53,909 --> 02:31:56,935
I could tell you something like,
the other day he wanted to kill me.

1762
02:31:57,045 --> 02:31:59,775
- Something like that.
- Why'd he want to kill you?

1763
02:31:59,881 --> 02:32:02,281
Because I took his picture.

1764
02:32:02,384 --> 02:32:05,945
He said, "If you take
my picture again...

1765
02:32:06,054 --> 02:32:08,579
I'm gonna kill you."

1766
02:32:08,690 --> 02:32:10,590
And he meant it.

1767
02:32:12,294 --> 02:32:14,990
See, just lay cool.
Lay cool.

1768
02:32:15,096 --> 02:32:17,064
Lay back. Dig it.

1769
02:32:17,165 --> 02:32:20,032
He gets friendly again.
He really does.

1770
02:32:20,135 --> 02:32:23,468
But you don't- you don't-
you don't judge the colonel.

1771
02:32:23,572 --> 02:32:26,234
You don't judge the colonel
like an ordinary man.

1772
02:32:33,048 --> 02:32:35,642
Okay, watch it now.
These are Americans. Americans!

1773
02:32:35,750 --> 02:32:38,583
You can feel the vibe
of this place.

1774
02:32:38,687 --> 02:32:42,088
Let me take your picture. Hey,
could you hold- Hey, hello. Hello.

1775
02:32:42,190 --> 02:32:44,090
Could you hold up
a minute?

1776
02:33:06,147 --> 02:33:07,546
Colby.

1777
02:33:23,665 --> 02:33:25,394
The heads.

1778
02:33:25,500 --> 02:33:27,695
You're looking at the heads.

1779
02:33:27,802 --> 02:33:30,999
I, uh- Sometimes
he goes too far.

1780
02:33:31,106 --> 02:33:33,802
He's the first one
to admit it.

1781
02:33:34,910 --> 02:33:37,811
- He's gone crazy.
- Wrong, wrong!

1782
02:33:39,147 --> 02:33:42,014
If you could have heard
the man just two days ago-

1783
02:33:42,117 --> 02:33:44,745
if you could have heard
him then, God-

1784
02:33:44,853 --> 02:33:48,118
- You were gonna call him crazy?
- Fuckin' A!

1785
02:33:50,225 --> 02:33:52,557
I just wanna talk to him.

1786
02:33:53,895 --> 02:33:57,194
Well, man, he's gone away.

1787
02:33:57,299 --> 02:34:00,029
He's gone away. He disappeared
out in the jungle with his people.

1788
02:34:00,135 --> 02:34:03,229
- I'll wait for him.
- He feels comfortable with his people.

1789
02:34:03,338 --> 02:34:06,239
He forgets himself
with his people.

1790
02:34:07,609 --> 02:34:10,373
- He forgets himself.
- Captain?

1791
02:34:10,478 --> 02:34:13,470
Maybe we should wait
back at the boat.

1792
02:34:13,581 --> 02:34:15,071
- I think you should-
- Okay, Chef.

1793
02:34:15,183 --> 02:34:17,413
We'll go back to the boat
for a while.

1794
02:34:17,519 --> 02:34:20,249
Yeah, stay with Lance.

1795
02:34:43,244 --> 02:34:46,008
This colonel guy,
he's wacko, man.

1796
02:34:46,114 --> 02:34:48,674
He's worse than crazy.
He's evil!

1797
02:34:48,783 --> 02:34:51,217
I mean, that's what the man's got
set up here, man!

1798
02:34:51,319 --> 02:34:53,787
It's fuckin' pagan idolatry.
Look around you!

1799
02:34:54,823 --> 02:34:58,020
- Shit, he's loco.
- Then you'll help me?

1800
02:34:58,126 --> 02:35:01,220
Fuckin' A, I'll help you. I'll do
anything to get out of this joint.

1801
02:35:01,329 --> 02:35:04,526
- Good boy.
- We could blow all them assholes away.

1802
02:35:04,632 --> 02:35:08,466
They're so fuckin' spaced out,
they wouldn't even know it.

1803
02:35:08,570 --> 02:35:13,200
I ain't afraid of all them
fuckin' skulls and altars and shit.

1804
02:35:14,843 --> 02:35:18,745
I used to think if I died
in an evil place...

1805
02:35:18,847 --> 02:35:22,044
then my soul wouldn't be able
to make it to Heaven.

1806
02:35:22,150 --> 02:35:25,381
But now, fuck-

1807
02:35:26,955 --> 02:35:29,924
I mean, I don't care where it goes,
as long as it ain't here.

1808
02:35:30,025 --> 02:35:33,825
So what do you wanna do?
I'll kill the fuck.

1809
02:35:33,928 --> 02:35:36,863
- Get out of here.
- I'm gonna need you to wait here, Chef.

1810
02:35:36,965 --> 02:35:41,299
I'll go up with Lance and
scrounge around, check the place out.

1811
02:35:41,403 --> 02:35:43,837
See if I can find
the colonel, okay?

1812
02:35:45,140 --> 02:35:48,166
Well, what do you
want me to do?

1813
02:35:48,276 --> 02:35:51,439
Here. You take the radio...

1814
02:35:51,546 --> 02:35:55,812
and if I don't get back
by 2200 hours...

1815
02:35:57,385 --> 02:35:59,979
you call in the air strike.

1816
02:36:01,356 --> 02:36:04,120
"Air strike?"

1817
02:36:04,225 --> 02:36:06,125
The code is "Almighty"...

1818
02:36:06,227 --> 02:36:09,628
coordinates zero-niner-two-six-
four-seven-one-two.

1819
02:36:09,731 --> 02:36:11,892
It's all in there.

1820
02:36:13,435 --> 02:36:17,462
Zero-niner-two-six-
four-seven-one-two.

1821
02:36:24,746 --> 02:36:28,682
<i>Everything I saw told me
that Kurtz had gone insane.</i>

1822
02:36:32,353 --> 02:36:34,412
<i>The place was full of bodies-</i>

1823
02:36:34,522 --> 02:36:38,720
<i>North Vietnamese,
Vietcong, Cambodians.</i>

1824
02:36:45,733 --> 02:36:50,102
<i>If I was still alive,
it was because he wanted me that way.</i>

1825
02:37:23,304 --> 02:37:27,001
<i>It smelled like
slow death in there-</i>

1826
02:37:27,108 --> 02:37:29,440
<i>malaria...</i>

1827
02:37:29,544 --> 02:37:31,444
<i>and nightmares.</i>

1828
02:37:33,348 --> 02:37:36,249
<i>This was the end
of the river, all right.</i>

1829
02:37:49,697 --> 02:37:51,927
Where are you from, Willard?

1830
02:37:56,771 --> 02:37:59,239
I'm from Ohio, sir.

1831
02:38:04,212 --> 02:38:06,544
Were you born there?

1832
02:38:06,648 --> 02:38:08,843
Yes, sir.

1833
02:38:08,950 --> 02:38:11,145
Whereabouts?

1834
02:38:11,252 --> 02:38:13,152
Toledo, sir.

1835
02:38:19,160 --> 02:38:21,720
How far are you
from the river?

1836
02:38:27,869 --> 02:38:29,769
The Ohio River, sir?

1837
02:38:32,106 --> 02:38:34,006
About 200 miles.

1838
02:38:41,849 --> 02:38:45,080
I went down that river
